SIMPLE: skip
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Skip
<hw>Skip</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See
<er>Skep</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A basket. See
<er>Skep</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Prov. Eng. & Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A basket on wheels, used in cotton
factories.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>An iron bucket, which slides
between guides, for hoisting mineral and rock.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Sugar Manuf.)</fld> <def>A charge of sirup in the
pans.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A beehive; a skep.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Skip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Skip
<hw>Skip</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Skipped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Skipping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>skippen</ets>, of
uncertain origin; cf. Icel. <ets>skopa</ets> run, <ets>skoppa</ets> to
spin like a top, OSw. & dial. Sw. <ets>skimmpa</ets> to run,
<ets>skimpa</ets>, <ets>skompa</ets>, to hop, skip; or Ir.
<ets>sgiob</ets> to snatch, Gael. <ets>sgiab</ets> to start or move
suddenly, to snatch, W. <ets>ysgipio</ets> to snatch.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To leap lightly; to move in leaps and hounds; -- commonly implying
a sportive spirit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The lamb thy riot dooms to bleed to-day,⟦br⟧
Had he thy reason, would he <qex>skip</qex> and play?</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So she drew her mother away <qex>skipping</qex>, dancing, and
frisking fantastically.</q> <rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: To leave matters unnoticed, as in reading,
speaking, or writing; to pass by, or overlook, portions of a thing; --
often followed by <xex>over</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Skip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Skip
<hw>Skip</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To leap lightly over;
<as>as, to <ex>skip</ex> the rope</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To pass over or by without notice; to omit; to miss;
<as>as, to <ex>skip</ex> a line in reading; to <ex>skip</ex> a
lesson</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They who have a mind to see the issue may <qex>skip</qex> these
two chapters.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Burnet.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cause to skip; <as>as, to <ex>skip</ex> a
stone</as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Skip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Skip
<hw>Skip</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A light leap or
bound.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act of passing over an interval from one thing
to another; an omission of a part.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A passage from one sound to
another by more than a degree at once.</def>
<rj><au>Busby.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Skip kennel</b></col>, <cd>a lackey; a footboy.</cd>
<mark>[Slang.]</mark> <au>Swift.</au> -- <col><b>Skip
mackerel</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Bluefish</er>,
1.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Skipjack</ent>⟦br⟧
